t metadata. JDK methods might already support reflective invoke on public methods since they could be built-in types. However, I wonder if methods like `StringBuilder.append` would still require reflection metadata. It's probably safer to use our own test class with explicit metadata for better control.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Exploring metadata minimization**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm considering how to minimize metadata entries. Maybe I can use `java.lang.String#concat(String)` or `java.util.ArrayList#add(Object)` since they might be reflectively invocable by default. But I'm not entirely sure if future-defaults and complete-reflection types would work seamlessly. If I have a `Method` object obtained from `Class.getMethod` on a JDK class, I wonder if I can invoke it as needed later. It's a bit uncertain, but I'm cautiously optimistic about these options!\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Considering String.concat usage**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm thinking about whether to use the current custom target or switch to `String.concat`. If I opt for `String.concat`, I can avoid concerns about side effects and ensure that it returns a new string. It seems like an easy assertion to make, so maybe it’s best to go with `String.concat`. I'll evaluate how this aligns with my goals moving forward!\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Considering commit modifications**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm thinking it might be better to modify my approach and create a second commit instead. It feels like I'm trying to respect the integrity of the first one. I don't really need to rewrite history unless someone specifically asks me to do so. It's more about ensuring everything is clear and straightforward for anyone who might review the changes later. Let’s go ahead and make sure this feels right!\\\\\\\"}]}\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \